Late Pleistocene,geological,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Alor_Pleistocene_HumanSkull.pdf,2,"direction of this movement is still debated. Here, we report on human skeletal material recovered from excavations at two rockshelters, known locally as Tron Bon Lei, on Alor Island, Indonesia. The remains, dated to the Late Pleistocene, are the ﬁrst anatomically modern human remains recovered in Wallacea dated to this period and are associated with cultural material demonstrating intentional burial. The human remains from Tron Bon Lei represent a popu"
Late Pleistocene,geological,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Alor_Pleistocene_HumanSkull.pdf,2,"man remains recovered in Wallacea dated to this period and are associated with cultural material demonstrating intentional burial. The human remains from Tron Bon Lei represent a population osteometrically distinct from Late Pleistocene Sunda and Sahul AMH. Instead, morphomet- rically, they appear more similar to Holocene populations in the Lesser Sundas. Thus, they may represent the remains of a population originally from Sunda whose Lesser Sunda Isla"
Holocene,geological,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Alor_Pleistocene_HumanSkull.pdf,2,"l demonstrating intentional burial. The human remains from Tron Bon Lei represent a population osteometrically distinct from Late Pleistocene Sunda and Sahul AMH. Instead, morphomet- rically, they appear more similar to Holocene populations in the Lesser Sundas. Thus, they may represent the remains of a population originally from Sunda whose Lesser Sunda Island descendants survived into the Holocene. © 2019 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved. 1."
Holocene,geological,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/Alor_Pleistocene_HumanSkull.pdf,2,"rphomet- rically, they appear more similar to Holocene populations in the Lesser Sundas. Thus, they may represent the remains of a population originally from Sunda whose Lesser Sunda Island descendants survived into the Holocene. © 2019 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved. 1. Introduction The Late Pleistocene migration of anatomically modern humans (AMH) from Africa to mainland Southeast Asia and into Australia is of great paleoanthropological in"
