Pleistocene,geological,,,"data/google-drive-pdfs/Asian Paleoanthropology From Africa to China and Beyond (Christopher J. Norton, David R. Braun (auth.) etc.) (z-lib.org).pdf",142,"ied by dispersing African populations. This study evaluates patterns of hominin morphology through a morphometric comparative analysis of the Hathnora specimen found along the Narmada River, and the only fairly complete Pleistocene fossil from South Asia. This fossil is compared to a sample of Old World Pleistocene specimens as well as Early Holocene South Asians and Andaman Islanders to elucidate patterns of variation both across space and throug"
Pleistocene,geological,,,"data/google-drive-pdfs/Asian Paleoanthropology From Africa to China and Beyond (Christopher J. Norton, David R. Braun (auth.) etc.) (z-lib.org).pdf",142,"ology through a morphometric comparative analysis of the Hathnora specimen found along the Narmada River, and the only fairly complete Pleistocene fossil from South Asia. This fossil is compared to a sample of Old World Pleistocene specimens as well as Early Holocene South Asians and Andaman Islanders to elucidate patterns of variation both across space and through time. The results indicate that the Narmada homi- nin from Hathnora exhibits a mix"
Early Holocene,geological,,,"data/google-drive-pdfs/Asian Paleoanthropology From Africa to China and Beyond (Christopher J. Norton, David R. Braun (auth.) etc.) (z-lib.org).pdf",142,"arative analysis of the Hathnora specimen found along the Narmada River, and the only fairly complete Pleistocene fossil from South Asia. This fossil is compared to a sample of Old World Pleistocene specimens as well as Early Holocene South Asians and Andaman Islanders to elucidate patterns of variation both across space and through time. The results indicate that the Narmada homi- nin from Hathnora exhibits a mix of Southeast Asian and sub-Saharan A"
Pleistocene,geological,,,"data/google-drive-pdfs/Asian Paleoanthropology From Africa to China and Beyond (Christopher J. Norton, David R. Braun (auth.) etc.) (z-lib.org).pdf",142,"that the Narmada homi- nin from Hathnora exhibits a mix of Southeast Asian and sub-Saharan African features. These results are consistent with India’s location between these two regions. A unique evolutionary model for Pleistocene Homo in India is proposed, incorporating the fact that this region was at a geographic crossroads, and predicting that the morphology found there will not conform to patterns found in other parts of Asia. Rather, morpho"
Pleistocene,geological,,,"data/google-drive-pdfs/Asian Paleoanthropology From Africa to China and Beyond (Christopher J. Norton, David R. Braun (auth.) etc.) (z-lib.org).pdf",142,"ing the fact that this region was at a geographic crossroads, and predicting that the morphology found there will not conform to patterns found in other parts of Asia. Rather, morphological evolutionary trajectories for Pleistocene South Asian hominins are expected to reflect a blend of African and Asian traits. Keywords Narmada • Homo heidelbergensis • Middle Pleistocene • Homo erectus • Multidirectional dispersals Introduction It is a well-known"
Middle Pleistocene,geological,,,"data/google-drive-pdfs/Asian Paleoanthropology From Africa to China and Beyond (Christopher J. Norton, David R. Braun (auth.) etc.) (z-lib.org).pdf",142,"s found in other parts of Asia. Rather, morphological evolutionary trajectories for Pleistocene South Asian hominins are expected to reflect a blend of African and Asian traits. Keywords Narmada • Homo heidelbergensis • Middle Pleistocene • Homo erectus • Multidirectional dispersals Introduction It is a well-known fact in paleoanthropology that very few hominin fossil remains are known from India dating to the Early and Middle Pleistocene. As such, paleo"
Middle Pleistocene,geological,,,"data/google-drive-pdfs/Asian Paleoanthropology From Africa to China and Beyond (Christopher J. Norton, David R. Braun (auth.) etc.) (z-lib.org).pdf",142,"idelbergensis • Middle Pleistocene • Homo erectus • Multidirectional dispersals Introduction It is a well-known fact in paleoanthropology that very few hominin fossil remains are known from India dating to the Early and Middle Pleistocene. As such, paleoanthropologists have a difficult time making inferences about the earliest hominin migrations and lifeways into this region based on the fossil evidence. The oldest known specimen from South Asia is the N"
