Pleistocene,geological,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/archaeologysulawesi.pdf,19,"Preface Sue O’Connor, David Bulbeck and Juliet Mayer Sulawesi has a unique place in the archaeology of Island Southeast Asia (ISEA). During the Pleistocene, when lower sea levels created a continuous land mass from Sumatra to Borneo, Sulawesi remained isolated by sea, but its long coastline, rich ecology and proximity to Borneo made it a promising destination for colonists"
Holocene,geological,,,data/google-drive-pdfs/archaeologysulawesi.pdf,19,"solated by sea, but its long coastline, rich ecology and proximity to Borneo made it a promising destination for colonists and an ideal way station for onward seaborne travel to the east. When sea levels rose during the Holocene, producing the current geographical configuration of ISEA, Sulawesi’s central location placed it at the crossroads of the maritime migrations that spread new languages and technological skills across this island realm."
